04765nam a22008175i 9780823272686DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232726867 a10.1515/97808232726862doi  a(DE-B1597)555105  a(OCoLC)961105731  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR421b.M29 2017eb 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a820.9/0032231 aMcEleney, Corey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFutile Pleasures :bEarly Modern Literature and the Limits of Utility /cCorey McEleney. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFutilitarianism: An Introduction -- t1. Pleasure without Profit -- t2. Bonfire of the Vanities -- t3. Art for Nothing’s Sake -- t4. Spenser’s Unhappy Ends -- t5. Beyond Sublimation -- tCoda: Less Matter, More Art -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHonorable Mention, 2018 MLA Prize for a First BookAgainst the defensive backdrop of countless apologetic justifications for the value of literature and the humanities, Futile Pleasures reframes the current conversation by returning to the literary culture of early modern England, a culture whose defensive posture toward literature rivals and shapes our own.During the Renaissance, poets justified the value of their work on the basis of the notion that the purpose of poetry is to please and instruct, that it must be both delightful and useful. At the same time, many of these writers faced the possibility that the pleasures of literature may be in conflict with the demand to be useful and valuable. Analyzing the rhetoric of pleasure and the pleasure of rhetoric in texts by William Shakespeare, Roger Ascham, Thomas Nashe, Edmund Spenser, and John Milton, McEleney explores the ambivalence these writers display toward literature’s potential for useless, frivolous vanity. Tracing that ambivalence forward to the modern era, this book also shows how contemporary critics have recapitulated Renaissance humanist ideals about aesthetic value. Against a longstanding tradition that defensively advocates for the redemptive utility of literature, Futile Pleasures both theorizes and performs the queer pleasures of futility. Without ever losing sight of the costs of those pleasures, McEleney argues that playing with futility may be one way of moving beyond the impasses that modern humanists, like their early modern counterparts, have always faced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aPleasure in literature. 0aSenses and sensation in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aQueer Theory. 4aRenaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aRenaissance Literature.  adeconstruction.  afutility.  apleasure.  aqueer theory.  aromance.  avanity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327268640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823272686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823272686/original  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK